The paper deals with distributed computing and consensus algorithms, which are typically studied in the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category. The problem of Byzantine consensus involves communication and agreement on values, which are also studied in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also discusses synchronous and asynchronous systems, which are studied in the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. The use of reliable and FIFO communication channels involves information theory, which is studied in the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Finally, the complete graph communication network and the use of simpler communication patterns suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category.
